By the Law of Cosines on triangle $ABE$, we have $BE^2 = 25 + 9 - 2 \cdot 5 \cdot 3 \cos \angle AEB = 49 - 30 \cos \angle AEB$.

By the Law of Cosines on triangle $CBE$, we have $BE^2 = 9 + 3^2 - 2 \cdot 3 \cdot 3 \cos \angle CEB = 24 - 18 \cos \angle CEB$.

Setting these two expressions for $BE^2$ equal, we get $49 - 30 \cos \angle AEB = 24 - 18 \cos \angle CEB$.  Since $\angle AEB + \angle CEB = 180^\circ$, we have $\cos \angle CEB = -\cos \angle AEB$, so $49 - 30 \cos \angle AEB = 24 + 18 \cos \angle AEB$.  Solving, we find $\cos \angle AEB = \frac{1}{7}$.

By the Law of Cosines on triangle $ABE$, we have $AE^2 = 25 + 9 - 2 \cdot 5 \cdot 3 \cos \angle AEB = 49$, so $AE = 7$.

By the Law of Cosines on triangle $AEC$, we have $CE^2 = 49 + 49 - 2 \cdot 7 \cdot 7 \cos \angle AEC = 98 - 98 \cos \angle AEC$.  Since $\angle AEC = 180^\circ - \angle AEB$, we have $\cos \angle AEC = -\cos \angle AEB = -\frac{1}{7}$, so $CE^2 = 98 + 14 = 112$, and $CE = 4 \sqrt{7}$.

By the Law of Cosines on triangle $CDE$, we have $DE^2 = 9 + 25 - 2 \cdot 3 \cdot 5 \cos \angle CED = 49 - 30 \cos \angle CED$.  Since $\angle CED = 180^\circ - \angle AEB$, we have $\cos \angle CED = -\cos \angle AEB = -\frac{1}{7}$, so $DE^2 = 49 + 6 = 55$, and $DE = \sqrt{55}$.

