We can complete the square on both equations to get\begin{align*}
(x-3)^2 + (y-4)^2 &= 25 \\
(x-5)^2 + (y+2)^2 &= 25
\end{align*}The first equation represents a circle with center $(3,4)$ and radius $5$, and the second equation represents a circle with center $(5,-2)$ and radius $5$.  The circles intersect at two points, and the minimum value of $h+k$ occurs when the two circles are tangent to each other.  In this case, the distance between the centers of the circles is equal to the sum of their radii, which is $10$.  The distance between the centers of the circles is $\sqrt{(5-3)^2 + (-2-4)^2} = \sqrt{4+36} = \sqrt{40} = 2\sqrt{10}$, so the circles are not tangent.  However, we can make the circles tangent by moving the second circle so that its center is at $(3,4)$.  In this case, the minimum value of $h+k$ is $25+25 = \boxed{50}$.  (Note that the circles are tangent when $h=k=25$.)[asy]
